<div class="text" id="1.1.2">
<span class="pagehead">Conferences :: Keynotes</span><br><br>
<span class="head">The Voice and the Vision</span><br><br>
The keynotes seemed like fun and games&mdash;just ask Sony President Kunitake Ando and Drew Barrymore, or Bill Gates and Shaquil O'Neil, or Craig Barrett and the troupe of Elvis impersonators. But these addresses were as informative as they were entertaining. 
<br><br>
<b>Link to transcripts below or order your audio recording from <a href="http://www.mobiltape.com/shop/products.asp?strCategory=Technology&strShowName=Consumer+Electronics+Show+%2A+Las+Vegas+2003" target="new">Mobiltape</a>.</b>
<br>
<a name="gates"></a><br>
<img src="/conferences/images/keynotes/microsoft-new.jpg" align="left"><br>
<b>Bill Gates</b><br>
Chairman and Chief Software Architect<br>
Microsoft Corp.<br>
Wednesday, January 8, 6:30 p.m.<br>
Las Vegas Hilton Theater<br><br>
<a href="Remarks by Bill Gates.doc" target="new">Read Transcript</a><br><br>
Sharing thoughts on creating a "smarter" lifestyle for consumers, Gates looks to advances in devices, connectivity, and services, including the highly anticipated launch of Smart Personal Objects Technology (SPOT).
<br><br><div align="center"><img src="/global_images/page_sep_onpage.gif" width="80%" height="1"></div><br>

<a name="ando"></a>
<table border="0" width="85%" align="center">
<tr>
	<td align="center" valign="top" width="50%">
		<img src="/conferences/images/keynotes/shapiro.jpg" align=""><br>
		<b>Gary Shapiro</b><br>
		President and CEO<br>
		Consumer Electronics Association (CEA)<br>
		<a href="Garys_2003_CES_opening_FINAL.doc" target="new">Read Transcript</a><br><br>
	</td>
	<td align="center" valign="top">
		<img src="/conferences/images/keynotes/gornik.jpg" align=""><br>
		<b>Kathy Gornik</b><br>
		CEA Board of Directors and<br>Executive Board CEA chairman<br>
		Thiel Audio Products President<br>
		<a href="Chairmans_Welcome_Gornik_FINAL.doc" target="new">Read Transcript</a><br><br>
	</td>
</tr>
</table>
For CEA President Gary Shapiro, evolution, expansion and optimism are among the short list of words that best describe the International CES and the industry it serves. Shapiro reveals projections, trends and transitions in his address while CEA Chairman of the Board and president of Thiel Audio Kathy Gornik discusses the critical role CES plays in the success of her company and market&mdash;and how her experience can be a compelling case study for other consumer technology businesses.
<br><br>
<img src="/conferences/images/keynotes/sony-new.jpg" align="left"><br>
<b>Kunitake Ando</b><br>
President and COO<br>
Sony Corp.<br>
Thursday, January 9, 8:30 a.m.<br>
Las Vegas Hilton Theater<br><br>
View Sony's <a href="http://news.sel.sony.com/pressrelease/3174" target="new">press release</a> and <a href="http://www.cnet.com/video/ces03/redirect/ando1.html" target="new">video clip</a><br><br>
Sony's concept of putting consumers at the center of the digital experience came to light thanks to Ando's opening keynote address&mdash;and a little help from actress Drew Barrymore, music group Mary Mary and a host of Sony's interactive digital products.
<br><br><div align="center"><img src="/global_images/page_sep_onpage.gif" width="80%" height="1"></div><br>

<a name="barret"></a>
<img src="/conferences/images/keynotes/intel-new.jpg" align="left"><br>
<b>Craig Barrett</b><br>
CEO<br>
Intel<br>
Thursday, January 9, 4:30 p.m.<br>
Las Vegas Hilton Theater<br><br>
<a href="Remarks by Craig Barrett.doc" target="new">Read Transcript</a><br><br>
Barrett and a pack of Elvis impersonators took center stage at the Las Vegas Hilton to "Unwire the Consumer." He cited the influx of new devices and opportunities created by the convergence of computing and consumer electronics as the main factor creating the wireless lifestyle. All consumers will be digital consumers, predicted Barrett.
<br><br><div align="center"><img src="/global_images/page_sep_onpage.gif" width="80%" height="1"></div><br>

<!--<a name="carter"></a>
<img src="/conferences/images/keynotes/stephen-carter.jpg" align="left"><br>
<b>Stephen Carter</b><br>
President and CEO<br>
Cingular Wireless<br>
Friday, January 10, 9:00 a.m.<br>
Las Vegas Hilton Theater<br><br><br>
Under Stephen Carter's leadership, Cingular Wireless has become one of the most recognizable brand names in the United States. Cingular Wireless now serves more than 22 million voice and data customers nationwide. Wireless technology has connected us all, but what's its next big step?
<br><br>-->

<a name="engibous"></a>
<img src="/conferences/images/keynotes/ti-new.jpg" align="left"><br>
<b>Tom Engibous</b><br>
Chairman, President, and CEO<br>
Texas Instruments Inc.<br>
Friday, January 10, 9:00 a.m.<br>
Las Vegas Hilton Theater<br><br>
<a href="remarks by enigbous.doc" target="new">Read Transcript</a>
<br><br>
Engibous says signal processing has become the technology of choice for digital audio, video, imaging, cell phones, broadband communications and wireless networking.  He demonstrated several new devices to illustrate how signal processing brings Internet connectivity to CE products and increases their functionality.
<br><br>

